The series of catalysts were considered to be a promising catalytic material in terms of activity and selectivity without addition of alkali. We used a custom quartz glass reactor (50 mL) and evaluated the catalytic performance of catalysts in an alkali-free solution for glycerol oxidation. The mass of the catalysts were calculated based on the glycerol/Pt molar ratio of 500:1, and then the catalysts were added to the reactor with 5 mL glycerol solution (0.3 M glycerol in 1000 mL ultra-pure water). The reactor was then purged with pure oxygen for 20 s and maintained the pressure at 0.1 MPa. The resulting transparent mixture was then diluted with deionized water to 1/20 of the initial concentration. High pressure liquid chromatography (HPLC) with the type of Shimazu LC-20AT was employed in tandem analysis. The analysis of the reaction mixture was carried out using an Agilent Zarbox SAX column, which internal size is 4.6 mm × 250 mm, 5 μm. At the condition of 30 °C, an aqueous solution of H3PO4 (0.1 % w/w) and pure acetonitrile (1.0 mL/min) were used as the eluent. External calibration method was employed to analyze the quantification of reactants and products [14]. By calculating the consumption of glycerol over per unit of exposed Pt sites, the turnover frequency (TOF) was determined. Glycerol conversion, selectivity of product, product yield, and TOF were calculated by the following equations:

                              Conversion glycerol (%) = mol glycerol converted/mol glycerol in feed×100;




                              Selectivity product (%) = mol product formed/mol glycerol converted×100;




                              Yield product (%) = Conversion glycerol (%) × Selectivity products (%)/100;




                              TOF = mol glycerol converted /[mol surface Pt atoms × time];




                              mol surface Pt atoms = D × mCat × X/MPt;

For the purpose of giving the size and distribution of nanoparticles more intuitively, TEM characterization was carried out. Specifically, Pt nanoparticles uniformly dispersed on the support with quite similar size were shown by TEM images in Fig. 1. Notably, compared with the samples reduced at relatively lower temperature, the size of nanoparticles over PtZn@ZnTiOx/ZnTiO3(800) fluctuated slightly without obvious agglomeration, as shown in Fig. 1E–H [33]. The dispersion of metal was then calculated on the basis of average nanoparticle size observed in HRTEM images (Table 1
                        ). It can be seen that the change of support crystal type has no obvious effect on the dispersion of metals, but a significant effect on the composition of active component. Concretely, as illustrated in Fig. S2, the lattice fringe (0.225 nm) of nanoparticles corresponding to Pt (111) plane was observed in Pt/ZnTi-MMO(300) and Pt/ZnTi-MMO(500) samples. In the case of PtZn/Zn2TiO4(700) and PtZn@ZnTiOx/ZnTiO3(800) samples, the lattice fringe spacing exposed by the metal nanoparticles are 0.217 nm and 0.214 nm, respectively, which located between Pt(111) and Zn (101), indicating the existence of PtZn alloys. Therefore, it is speculated that the PtCl6
                        2- species were primarily reduced to Pt nanoparticles, then gradually transformed to PtZn alloy due to the partial reduction of zinc as the reduction temperature increases [34].

According to the above results, the reasons for the performance improvement of glycerol high-efficiency directional oxidation to glyceric acid over PtZn@ZnTiOx/ZnTiO3 catalyst was concluded (shown as Scheme 2
                        ). Initially, the enhancement of glycerol oxidation activity can be attributed to the formation of O2
                        − active oxygen species, which facilitates the activation and dissociation of O2 molecules on the surface of the PtZn alloy nanoparticles. Meanwhile, abundant oxygen vacancies on the low-coordination interface structure promoted the storage and mobility of active oxygen species. Moreover, the glyceraldehyde species adsorbed at the low-coordination interface were highly dissociated in the advantageous bidentate form, which promoted the transformation of intermediate glyceraldehyde to glyceric acid. In conclusion, the synergistic effect of PtZn alloy and low-coordination interface site on facilitating oxygen activation and glyceraldehyde adsorption play an essential role in achieving high yield of continuous oxidation product (GLYA).
